id: verify
title: tnl verify — structural and test-binding checks
scope: feature
owners: [@jana]
paths: [src/verifier.ts, src/commands/verify.ts, src/index.ts]
surfaces: [tnl verify]
dependencies: [parser, resolve]

intent:
  `tnl verify` checks each TNL against the current filesystem and test
  sources. Tier 1 confirms every `paths:` entry exists on disk and
  every `dependencies:` entry points to a real TNL. Tier 2 opens the
  file referenced by each `test-backed` clause and verifies the test
  name string is present. The verifier does NOT execute tests —
  execution is the user's existing CI. The verifier catches
  structural drift: deleted paths, dangling dependencies, removed or
  renamed tests.

behaviors:
  - The verifier module MUST expose `verifyTnl(filePath: string, options?: VerifyOptions): UnitVerifyResult` and `verifyAll(options?: VerifyOptions & { ids?: string[] }): UnitVerifyResult[]`. `VerifyOptions` MUST include `{ cwd?: string }`; when `cwd` is not supplied, both functions MUST use `process.cwd()`.
  - `UnitVerifyResult` MUST have shape `{ id: string; sourcePath: string; checks: CheckResult[]; passed: number; failed: number; unchecked: number }`.
  - `CheckResult` MUST have shape `{ kind: 'unit' | 'clause'; name: string; class?: ClauseClass; status: 'passed' | 'failed' | 'unchecked'; reason?: string }`. For `kind: 'clause'`, `name` MUST be the clause id (`L-N`) and `class` MUST be populated from the resolved class.
  - The tier-1 `paths-exist` check MUST run once per TNL of scope `feature`. It MUST emit `passed` if every declared `paths:` entry resolves to a file or directory on disk (relative to `cwd`), or `failed` with a reason naming the missing path otherwise. `repo-wide` TNLs (which have no `paths:`) MUST skip this check entirely.
  - The tier-1 `dependencies-resolve` check MUST run once per TNL that declares any `dependencies:`. It MUST emit `passed` if every declared dependency id corresponds to a file `<cwd>/tnl/<id>.tnl`, or `failed` naming the dangling id otherwise. TNLs with no `dependencies:` MUST skip this check.
  - For each clause whose resolved class is `test-backed`, the verifier MUST open `testBinding.file` (resolved relative to `cwd`) and perform a literal-string search for `testBinding.name`. Found → `passed`. Not found → `failed` with reason `"declared test '<name>' not found in <file>"`. File missing → `failed` with reason `"test file <file> does not exist"`. Other read errors → `failed` with the underlying error message.
  - Clauses of class `structural`, `semantic`, or `advisory` MUST emit `unchecked` with a reason noting no deterministic check applies in this version. Unchecked is not a failure.
  - The CLI MUST register a `verify` subcommand against the default registry; `src/index.ts` MUST import the command module.
  - `tnl verify` with no positional args MUST verify every `.tnl` file directly under `./tnl/` (non-recursive). Positional args MAY be TNL ids (resolved to `./tnl/<id>.tnl`) or filesystem paths to `.tnl` files; the CLI MUST accept a mix.
  - When no `tnl/` directory exists and no positional args are provided, the CLI MUST print an error telling the user to run `tnl init` first and exit 2.
  - The CLI's stdout MUST include one summary line per unit of form `<id>: <P> passed, <F> failed, <U> unchecked`, and for every failed check a detail line of form `  <name> (<class>) FAIL: <reason>` (the `(<class>)` segment MUST be omitted for unit-level checks `paths-exist` / `dependencies-resolve`). At the end the CLI MUST print an overall summary: `Summary: <T> TNLs verified. <C> checks, <F> failed, <U> unchecked.`
  - The CLI MUST exit 2 if any check across any unit failed, else exit 0. Unchecked alone MUST NOT cause a non-zero exit.
  - On parser/resolver failure for an individual TNL in batch mode, the CLI MUST emit a single `<id-or-path>: FAIL — <error message>` line on stderr and continue to the next TNL. Overall exit MUST be 2 if any unit errored.
  - The verifier MUST NOT invoke an LLM, make network calls, execute tests, or introduce any runtime dependency beyond Node's standard library and modules already in the project.
  - Tests MUST cover: `paths-exist` passes when all paths exist; `paths-exist` fails naming the missing path; `paths-exist` skipped for repo-wide; `dependencies-resolve` passes when all deps exist; `dependencies-resolve` fails naming a dangling id; `dependencies-resolve` skipped when no deps; test-binding passes when name is found in file; test-binding fails when name is not in file; test-binding fails when file missing; clauses of class `structural`/`semantic`/`advisory` emit `unchecked`; CLI `tnl verify` with no args verifies all; CLI accepts id and path positional mix; CLI exit 0 on all-passing; CLI exit 2 on any failure; malformed `.tnl` under `./tnl/` reported per-unit on stderr and exits 2; per-unit summary and per-failure line formatting; no `tnl/` + no args → exit 2 with init hint.

non-goals:
  - Executing tests — the user's test runner owns that.
  - AST / tree-sitter checks — post-A5.
  - Route-handler mapping.
  - Symbol presence.
  - Per-clause text-predicate annotations.
  - Semantic (tier 3) adjudication.
  - `--verbose` / `--quiet` flags, color output, JSON output — deferred; one compact format.
  - Caching verify results across runs.

rationale:
  Why not execute tests: CI already does that. Duplicating it blurs
  responsibility and slows `tnl verify` proportionally to the test
  suite. The drift we want to catch is binding-level — did someone
  rename or delete the test the clause points at? A substring search
  against the test file catches that cheaply.

  Why substring search rather than AST inside the test file: same
  reason the outer design avoids tree-sitter — the check is "does
  the name appear verbatim in the file." Language-agnostic; works
  for Jest `it(...)`, pytest function names, Go `Test...` functions,
  RSpec `describe(...)`, or any other convention that spells the
  name as a literal.

  Why unchecked is not a failure: a TNL can legitimately have
  structural, advisory, or semantic clauses with no deterministic
  check in v1. Surfacing them as unchecked keeps output honest
  without painting CI red.

  Why the CLI accepts both ids and paths: agents typically have ids
  in hand (from `get_impacted_tnls` or `retrieve_tnl`); humans type
  paths. Accepting both removes a friction point.
